I don't know if we have any around, but...

39:05.032 --> 39:05.773
Do we have any here?

39:06.533 --> 39:06.774
Yeah.

39:07.354 --> 39:08.695
Should we show them one?

39:08.715 --> 39:09.015
Sure.

39:09.136 --> 39:10.357
It's in the other unit, though.

39:10.377 --> 39:10.437
Oh.

39:11.237 --> 39:12.158
You want to see what we've got?

39:12.198 --> 39:12.458
May I?

39:12.478 --> 39:12.939
Sure.

39:12.959 --> 39:13.139
Sure.

39:13.159 --> 39:17.142
I came to get one.

39:17.243 --> 39:25.630
I was, uh, came and the guy said, well, I'll give you a glass of champagne and you can catch the afternoon plane back to L.A.

39:25.670 --> 39:28.412
And I said, I'm here to work in the factory and on the floor.

39:29.093 --> 39:34.077
Well, after a few bottles of champagne, nine in the morning, uh,

39:34.276 --> 39:40.804
He realized I was going to stay, and I stayed for six weeks, and I learned how to make it.

39:41.004 --> 39:44.168
But my first assignment was in a dungeon with two guys.

39:44.228 --> 39:47.392
One was Flemish, and one was called the Company Idiot.

39:48.293 --> 39:56.123
And it was about the size of that area in there, 12 by 12, which had like a rack, a mechanical rack on it.

39:56.383 --> 39:58.526
It had an archery target and had a small window.

39:59.447 --> 40:00.629
And I knew what the window was for.

40:00.649 --> 40:01.249
That was light.

40:01.269 --> 40:02.511
It looked like a prison cell.

40:03.385 --> 40:04.707
I knew what the rack was for.

40:04.767 --> 40:06.889
There was a sort of slicing machine.

40:06.909 --> 40:10.554
There were big cakes like cheese with a wire bow.

40:11.275 --> 40:13.698
I didn't know what the archery target was for.

40:13.718 --> 40:19.265
So here are these two guys, five feet, five, big 200 pounds, both wooden clogs.

40:21.007 --> 40:22.789
And I asked, what was the archery?

40:22.809 --> 40:23.970
And they said, like this.

40:25.012 --> 40:30.138
And they both get this bow in there, this bow like, and they take the wire cutter through the bar.

40:30.639 --> 40:33.342
And as it goes through the end of this huge cake,

40:33.811 --> 40:38.576
goes twang, and, you know, 500 pounds goes against the wall.

40:38.596 --> 40:39.758
And they had to out shoot targets.

40:39.798 --> 40:44.063
So my note to myself was, have to change this process to the American.

40:45.064 --> 40:57.518
But anyway, you know, when they introduced me to the village or the company idiot, I heard him say something, and I realized I understood it.

40:58.399 --> 41:00.021
What he was speaking was Albanian.

41:00.372 --> 41:01.153
It's very close.

41:01.474 --> 41:05.782
And I understood Albanian because my Greek workmen were from Albania.

41:05.802 --> 41:08.688
So I started talking to him.

41:08.908 --> 41:15.681
Next day, all around through the factory there, the Plemish factory, there were two company idiots, him and me.

41:16.758 --> 41:19.281
Oh, Albanian is very, very close to it.

41:19.441 --> 41:21.763
Well, no, it's a really, it's a different root language.

41:22.044 --> 41:24.586
It is, but, I mean, the Greeks, they're up in that part of it.

41:24.606 --> 41:25.587
Oh, yeah, they're all mixed.

41:25.607 --> 41:27.689
They're called Epidotes.

41:27.710 --> 41:28.931
Right, and they all come down.

41:29.471 --> 41:32.675
They've been coming down, and they've been in the Peloponnesian now.

41:33.075 --> 41:38.301
They're going, spreading out in the islands because there's no money in Albanian.

41:38.521 --> 41:42.445
My mother's side is from the Peloponnesos down in Mani.

41:42.610 --> 42:03.041
It's not because he wanted to close, they just like tripled his rent, you know, and he just couldn't afford to do it.

42:03.061 --> 42:05.565
And there really is not a good Greek restaurant in Boston now.

42:05.585 --> 42:07.167
There's not a good Greek restaurant here.

42:07.619 --> 42:10.123
That one I went to a couple of years ago is pretty good.

42:12.246 --> 42:12.606
I forget the name.

42:12.626 --> 42:21.800
There is a new place on 3rd, down towards near La Brea, and it's called Sophie's.

42:22.541 --> 42:25.345
S-O-F-I-E, I think.

42:25.365 --> 42:25.846
Sophia.

42:26.787 --> 42:29.632
Yeah, but it's called Sophie's, and it's a Greek restaurant.

42:30.693 --> 42:33.237
Anyway, these were... You made these?

42:33.257 --> 42:33.357
Yeah.

42:34.180 --> 42:42.188
This is called A Latter-day, L-A-T-T-E-I-day, Chapbook, An Alphabet of Wishes from the Clotson Family, Lloyd, Joanne, Clarina.

42:42.208 --> 42:43.770
That could be a Greek name, too, you know.

42:43.790 --> 42:44.971
It is a Greek name, yes.

42:44.991 --> 42:45.451
Little girl.

42:45.992 --> 42:46.152
Yeah.

42:46.873 --> 42:50.857
Toby, Toby, E-Y, Eric, and you are published by the Occasional Press.

42:50.877 --> 42:51.638
Is this your press?

42:52.278 --> 42:52.859
No, it wasn't.

42:52.899 --> 42:55.041
We just had it printed by some commercial printers.

42:57.424 --> 42:59.906
And these things that you wrote that you wrote?

43:00.146 --> 43:00.627
Yeah, yeah.

43:00.647 --> 43:01.808
My wife did most of this.

43:04.201 --> 43:07.425
If wishes were horses, then beggars would ride.

43:08.146 --> 43:15.415
We wish you art, adventures, assurance, ability, appetite, and, oh, it goes on to the next one, B, we wish you blessings.

43:15.495 --> 43:16.336
This is very clever.

43:17.317 --> 43:19.300
Well, the clever part is my wife's.

43:19.320 --> 43:26.969
And then finally it ends up with Z, we wish you zeal, zest, xenocrelation, whatever one wishes it to me.

43:27.230 --> 43:30.273
Z-Y-N-O-C-R-I-L-L-A-T-I-U-R.

43:30.413 --> 43:33.297
It's 28 pages on this page.

43:33.952 --> 43:34.753
The date here, 1973.

43:34.773 --> 43:38.919
Now, did you send these out as Christmas greetings?

43:40.642 --> 43:41.042
Lovely.

43:42.124 --> 43:43.466
I'm glad you showed me these.

43:43.806 --> 43:45.569
How often did you do these?

43:45.649 --> 43:46.150
Once a year?

43:46.230 --> 43:48.253
Once a generation.

43:48.273 --> 43:50.256
The tragical death of an apple pie.

43:51.137 --> 43:52.900
And you wrote these as a family?

43:52.920 --> 43:53.020
Yeah.

43:53.561 --> 43:54.843
And produced them as a family?

43:54.863 --> 43:56.265
They made chop marks and prints.

43:56.365 --> 43:57.867
I think this one here may have been.

43:58.100 --> 44:01.883
And how many of these do you think you did, half a dozen, a dozen?

44:01.903 --> 44:04.085
No, we'd probably print it up, 100, 200.

44:04.786 --> 44:06.508
I mean, but how many different roles?

44:08.109 --> 44:10.111
Two I can see, but I don't know how many more.

44:10.531 --> 44:18.278
The tragical death of an apple pie, which was cut to pieces and eaten by 26 persons, with whom all young folks ought to be well acquainted.

44:18.298 --> 44:19.399
A, apple pie.

44:19.539 --> 44:20.180
B, bit it.

44:20.360 --> 44:20.921
C, cut it.

44:21.361 --> 44:22.342
D, dealt it.

44:22.362 --> 44:22.883
E, eat it.

44:23.543 --> 44:24.564
F, fought for it.

44:24.624 --> 44:26.706
G, got it all the way through to

44:28.222 --> 44:32.870
viewed it, wanted it, and then X, Y, and Z, and all wished for peace in hand.

44:32.890 --> 44:33.351
That's lovely.

44:35.134 --> 44:36.296
Are they all alphabet?

44:39.883 --> 44:39.963
Yes.

44:39.983 --> 44:45.392
It's written in 1974, an edition of 500, by the occasional press, Beverly Hills, California.

44:46.835 --> 44:48.478
Thank you for bringing me that.

44:48.538 --> 44:50.882
Yes, there he is.

44:50.902 --> 44:52.565
Okay, do you need to be back here?

44:52.585 --> 44:53.166
I will.

44:53.770 --> 44:54.475
I'll be in touch.

44:54.616 --> 44:54.898
Okay.

44:54.938 --> 44:56.831
And maybe I'll see you up in Sanford.

44:56.851 --> 44:58.059
Yeah, I'm going to be walking around.

44:58.079 --> 44:58.562
Thanks.

44:59.589 --> 44:59.730
Thanks.

